In [[Propositional calculus|propositional logic]], Frege's theorems refers to this [[tautology (logic)|tautology]]:

: (''P'' → (''Q''→''R'')) → ((''P''→''Q'') →  (''P''→''R''))

The [[truth table]] to the right gives a proof. For all possible assignments of ''false'' ({{n&}}) or ''true'' ({{y&}}) to ''P'', ''Q'', and ''R'' (columns 1, 3, 5), each subformula is evaluated according to the rules for [[material conditional]], the result being shown below its main operator. Column 6 shows that the whole formula evaluates to ''true'' in every case, i.e. that it is a tautology. In fact, its [[antecedent (logic)|antecedent]] (column 2) and its [[consequent]] (column 10) are even equivalent.

